# Shell scripts run inside Linux containers - must stay LF regardless of
# core.autocrlf, or they break on checkout (e.g. Docker build on Windows).
*.sh text eol=lf

# The codegen artifact is regenerated and byte-compared by CI, so its line
# endings cannot depend on who generated it. .prettierrc sets endOfLine=crlf, so
# prettier (which codegen.ts runs on the output) writes CRLF. On Windows
# core.autocrlf=true normalises that back to LF on the way into git, so the blob
# is LF and everything looks clean. On CI's Linux runner there is no autocrlf:
# the regenerated file keeps its CRLF, git diffs it against the LF blob, and all
# 2235 lines come back as changed - which is the "src/generated/graphql.ts is out
# of date" failure. Pinning the file to LF makes git's view of it identical on
# every machine.
src/generated/graphql.ts text eol=lf
